      "text": "An excellent and challenging choice. We are now moving from well-defined benchmarks into the realm of real-world scientific discovery.\n\nProtein-Protein Interaction (PPI) networks are a perfect test for the core idea of your paper: finding \"meaningful, structurally coherent, and detectable communities.\" In this context, a \"community\" isn\u0027t just a cluster of nodes; it\u0027s potentially a **molecular machine**—a group of proteins that work together to perform a specific biological function.\n\nUnlike our previous datasets, PPI networks typically **do not have a single, clean ground-truth partition**. A protein can be part of multiple complexes or pathways. Therefore, we cannot calculate a simple ARI score. Instead, our evaluation will be qualitative and exploratory, asking: **\"Does the structure found by the algorithm correspond to known biological functions?\"**\n\n### The Dataset: Yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae) PPI Network\n\nWe will use a classic, well-studied PPI network from the yeast organism. It\u0027s one of the most complete and well-understood interactomes, making it the \"hello, world\" of biological network analysis.\n\nOur experiment will proceed as follows:\n1.  **Load the Network:** We\u0027ll download the dataset and load it into a graph.\n2.  **Process the Network:** Biological networks are often fragmented. We will focus our analysis on the largest connected component (LCC), which is standard practice.\n3.  **Apply Structural Analysis:** We will run the Louvain algorithm to partition the LCC into communities.\n4.  **Analyze and Interpret:** We will visualize the results and, most importantly, outline how a biologist would determine if the detected communities are meaningful.\n\n---\n\n### Step 1 \u0026 2: Load and Process the Yeast PPI Network\n\nFirst, download the dataset file:\n1.  Go to the SNAP dataset page: [https://snap.stanford.edu/data/protein.html](https://snap.stanford.edu/data/protein.html)\n2.  Download `protein.Yeast.txt.gz`.\n3.  Unzip it. You should now have a file named `protein.Yeast.txt`. Place it in your working directory.\n\nThis file is a simple edge list, where each line represents an interaction between two proteins (identified by numeric IDs).\n\nThe following script will load this file, extract the largest connected component, and prepare it for analysis.\n\n```python\nimport networkx as nx\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport community as community_louvain\n\n# --- Step 1 \u0026 2: Load and Process the PPI Network ---\ntry:\n    # Load the graph from the edge list file.\n    # Note: The file uses integers as node labels.\n    G_raw \u003d nx.read_edgelist(\u0027protein.Yeast.txt\u0027, nodetype\u003dint)\n    print(\"Successfully loaded the raw Yeast PPI network.\")\n    print(f\"Raw graph has {G_raw.number_of_nodes()} nodes and {G_raw.number_of_edges()} edges.\")\n\n    # PPI networks are often disconnected. We\u0027ll analyze the largest connected component (LCC).\n    connected_components \u003d sorted(nx.connected_components(G_raw), key\u003dlen, reverse\u003dTrue)\n    G_lcc \u003d G_raw.subgraph(connected_components[0])\n\n    print(f\"\\nExtracted the Largest Connected Component (LCC).\")\n    print(f\"LCC has {G_lcc.number_of_nodes()} nodes and {G_lcc.number_of_edges()} edges.\")\n\nexcept FileNotFoundError:\n    print(\"ERROR: \u0027protein.Yeast.txt\u0027 not found.\")\n    print(\"Please download the file from https://snap.stanford.edu/data/protein.html\")\n    print(\"Then, unzip it and place the .txt file in the same directory as this script.\")\n    G_lcc \u003d None\n\n# --- Step 3: Apply Louvain Community Detection ---\nif G_lcc:\n    print(\"\\n--- Running Louvain Community Detection on the LCC ---\")\n    detected_partition \u003d community_louvain.best_partition(G_lcc, random_state\u003d42)\n    num_detected_communities \u003d len(set(detected_partition.values()))\n    print(f\"Louvain algorithm detected {num_detected_communities} communities (potential functional modules).\")\n\n    # --- Step 4: Analysis and Visualization ---\n    # Create a list of communities (lists of nodes) for further analysis\n    communities \u003d {}\n    for node, community_id in detected_partition.items():\n        if community_id not in communities:\n            communities[community_id] \u003d []\n        communities[community_id].append(node)\n    \n    # Print statistics on the detected communities\n    community_sizes \u003d [len(c) for c in communities.values()]\n    print(f\"Community sizes range from {min(community_sizes)} to {max(community_sizes)}.\")\n    print(f\"The 5 largest communities have sizes: {sorted(community_sizes, reverse\u003dTrue)[:5]}\")\n\n    # --- Visualization ---\n    # This graph is larger, so visualization will be dense.\n    # We use a spring layout with more iterations to spread it out.\n    print(\"\\nGenerating visualization... (this may take a moment)\")\n    plt.figure(figsize\u003d(15, 15))\n    \n    pos \u003d nx.spring_layout(G_lcc, iterations\u003d100, seed\u003d42)\n    \n    # Color nodes by their detected community ID\n    colors \u003d [detected_partition[node] for node in G_lcc.nodes()]\n\n    nx.draw(G_lcc, pos, node_color\u003dcolors, with_labels\u003dFalse, node_size\u003d20, width\u003d0.5, \n            cmap\u003dplt.cm.get_cmap(\u0027tab20\u0027, num_detected_communities))\n    \n    plt.title(f\"Detected Communities in Yeast PPI Network ({num_detected_communities} modules found)\")\n    plt.show()\n\n```\n\n### How to Run and What to Expect\n\n1.  After downloading and unzipping the data, run the script.\n2.  The script will first print statistics about the raw graph and its largest connected component.\n3.  It will then run the Louvain algorithm and report the number and sizes of the communities it found.\n4.  Finally, it will generate a large plot visualizing the detected communities. The plot will be dense, but it should reveal clear clusters of same-colored 